<br>
The &quot;moron&quot; implication was submitted before I was even aware of your response.  So no, it was not directed specifically toward you.  As Mill said, you seem like a nice enough guy and I hope there is no resentment between us.<br>
<br>
It's just really easy to get carried away and tear into someone when despite your agonizing efforts, they go right ahead and believe whatever the hell they want to believe, contrary to reason though it may be.  And no, I do have the market cornered on truth, or hold a monopoly over reason.  Just ask Suppreme Allah, who took me to the bank and back, about that.  It's just that when you've been doing this sort of thing as long as I have, you discover that reality for most people, myself included, is governed largely by misconception and that truth is often best administered by brute force.  It's a fact of life that I accept and feel neither compunction in the performance of this duty, nor indignation when the roles are reversed.<br>
<br>
So I have to ask, what makes you think that infiltrators will be nerfed?  It's almost as if you are encouraging the collective Shadowblade defense to pipe down and take one for the team?  Personally I feel that Infils do not need a nerf nor are they in any danger of being nerfed.  Your precious 2.5 spec/lvl points are safe, of that I am certain.<br>
<br>
What disturbs me, however, is the recent anti-nerf trend.  I'm sure every one of us has experienced a debilitating class nerf in some game or another.  It sucks.  You sacrifice not only money, but more importantly time, toward the development of a character only to be kicked in the teeth by the company with nothing more than an impersonal patch note for consolation.  It tends to leave you rather jaded and cynical about the company's concern for the player base, and for the most part, I'd say the cynicism is justified.  MMORPG's are just another Skinner's Box bundled with a glorified chat engine.  But to universally denounce &quot;nerfing&quot; is just naive, especially in games with pvp-centric designs.  Fault the designers and programmers all you want, it's just damn difficult to balance the multifaceted pvp experience which characterizes the games we all know and love, without endless fine tuning.  Scaling all classes upwards just doesn't work.  For one thing, that imbalances the PvE element.  For another, PvP is as dynamic as the people behind the avatars.  There will always be new and changing ways to exploit the intricacies of the endless class resources.  Scaling upwards would result in a ceiling-less growth as each class approached uniformity.  It's one of those idealistic concepts that is just not practical.<br>
<br>
So ya, F nerfs...that are injurious to overall balance.  But nerfs that improve the welfare of the game as a whole should not only be welcomed, but actively pursued (in the case that an upgrade is not judicious.)  And no, I'm not campaigning to nerf the infiltrator class, although I'm sure I'll be quoted in that context. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub175.ezboard.com/usunraven01.showPublicProfile?language=EN>SunRaven01</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(6/13/02 12:06:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3506.topic&index=72>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> &quot;If a thrust NS/infil can be even with a SB, then there is a balance problem. I would hope the SB would win fairly easily.&quot;<br>
